   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="edition" ana="#b1" xml:lang="grc" subtype="transcription" xml:id="elus0059.transcription" corresp="#elus0059.translation">
            <p>Θάρσι, <lb/>
               <choice>
                  <orig>Ὀμμο<lb break="no"/>σεείδη<lb/>
                     <unclear>σ</unclear>
                  </orig>
                  <corr>Ὀμμο<lb break="no"/>σεείδη</corr>
               </choice>, <expan>
                  <abbr>ὀδ</abbr>
                  <ex>ὶς</ex>
               </expan>
               <expan>
                  <abbr>ἀθ</abbr>
                     <ex>άνατο</ex>
                  <abbr>
                     <unclear>ς</unclear>
                  </abbr>
               </expan>
            </p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" ana="#b1" xml:id="elus0059.translation" corresp="#elus0059.transcription">
            <p>Courage, Umm Sa'id, no one is immortal</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The last letter on the last line of the inscription might not be a letter. The editor
               thinks that the use of the common formulae "Courage" and "no one is immortal" marks
               tombstones in this group as pre-Christian. "Umm Sa'id" in the inscription means
               "Mother of Sa'id".</p>
         </div>
